maze_dataset.tokenization

turning a maze into text

  • MazeTokenizerModular is the new recommended way to do this as of 1.0.0
  • legacy TokenizationMode enum and MazeTokenizer class for supporting existing code
  • a whole lot of helper classes and functions
View on GitHub 

 1"""turning a maze into text
 2
 3- `MazeTokenizerModular` is the new recommended way to do this as of 1.0.0
 4- legacy `TokenizationMode` enum and `MazeTokenizer` class for supporting existing code
 5- a whole lot of helper classes and functions
 6
 7"""

class TokenizationMode(enum.Enum):
View on GitHub 
68class TokenizationMode(Enum):
69    """LEGACY: mode of tokenization
70
71    # Abbreviations:
72    - `AOTP`: Ajacency list, Origin, Target, Path
73    - `UT`: Unique Token (for each coordiate)
74    - `CTT`: Coordinate Tuple Tokens (each coordinate is tokenized as a tuple of integers)
75
76    # Modes:
77    - `AOTP_UT_rasterized`: the "classic" mode: assigning tokens to each coordinate is done via rasterization
78        example: for a 3x3 maze, token order is `(0,0), (0,1), (0,2), (1,0), (1,1), (1,2), (2,0), (2,1), (2,2)`
79    - `AOTP_UT_uniform`: new mode, where a 3x3 tokenization scheme and 5x5 tokenizations scheme are compatible
80        uses `corner_first_ndindex` function to order the tokens
81    - `AOTP_CTT_indexed`: each coordinate is a tuple of integers
82    """
83
84    AOTP_UT_rasterized = "AOTP_UT_rasterized"
85    AOTP_UT_uniform = "AOTP_UT_uniform"
86    AOTP_CTT_indexed = "AOTP_CTT_indexed"
87
88    def to_legacy_tokenizer(self, max_grid_size: int | None = None):
89        return MazeTokenizer(tokenization_mode=self, max_grid_size=max_grid_size)

LEGACY: mode of tokenization

Abbreviations:

  • AOTP: Ajacency list, Origin, Target, Path
  • UT: Unique Token (for each coordiate)
  • CTT: Coordinate Tuple Tokens (each coordinate is tokenized as a tuple of integers)

Modes:

  • AOTP_UT_rasterized: the "classic" mode: assigning tokens to each coordinate is done via rasterization example: for a 3x3 maze, token order is (0,0), (0,1), (0,2), (1,0), (1,1), (1,2), (2,0), (2,1), (2,2)
  • AOTP_UT_uniform: new mode, where a 3x3 tokenization scheme and 5x5 tokenizations scheme are compatible uses corner_first_ndindex function to order the tokens
  • AOTP_CTT_indexed: each coordinate is a tuple of integers
AOTP_UT_rasterized = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_rasterized: 'AOTP_UT_rasterized'>
AOTP_UT_uniform = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_uniform: 'AOTP_UT_uniform'>
AOTP_CTT_indexed = <TokenizationMode.AOTP_CTT_indexed: 'AOTP_CTT_indexed'>

@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
class _TokenizerElement(muutils.json_serialize.serializable_dataclass.SerializableDataclass, abc.ABC):
View on GitHub 
458@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
459class _TokenizerElement(SerializableDataclass, abc.ABC):
460    """Superclass for tokenizer elements.
461    Subclasses contain modular functionality for maze tokenization.
462
463    # Development
464    Due to the functionality of `ALL_TOKENIZERS`, `_TokenizerElement` subclasses may only contain fields of type `utils.FiniteValued`.
465    Implementing a subclass with an `int` or `float`-typed field, for example, is not supported.
466    In the event that adding such fields is deemed necessary, `ALL_TOKENIZERS` must be updated.
467    """
468
469    @staticmethod
470    def _stringify(k: str, v: Any):
471        if isinstance(v, bool):
472            return f"{k}={str(v)[0]}"
473        if isinstance(v, _TokenizerElement):
474            return v.name
475        if isinstance(v, tuple):
476            return f"{k}={''.join(['(', *[str(x)+', ' for x in v], ')'])}"
477        else:
478            return f"{k}={v}"
479
480    @property
481    def name(self) -> str:
482        members_str: str = ", ".join(
483            [self._stringify(k, v) for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if k != "_type_"]
484        )
485        output: str = f"{type(self).__name__}({members_str})"
486        if "." in output and output.index("(") > output.index("."):
487            return "".join(output.split(".")[1:])
488        else:
489            return output
490
491    def __str__(self):
492        return self.name
493
494    def __init_subclass__(cls, **kwargs):
495        """
496        Hack: dataclass hashes don't include the class itself in the hash function inputs.
497        This causes dataclasses with identical fields but different types to hash identically.
498        This hack circumvents this by adding a slightly hidden field to every subclass with a value of `repr(cls)`.
499        To maintain compatibility with `all_instances`, the static type of the new field can only have 1 possible value.
500        So we type it as a singleton `Literal` type.
501        muutils 0.6.1 doesn't support `Literal` type validation, so `assert_type=False`.
502        Ignore Pylance complaining about the arg to `Literal` being an expression.
503        """
504        super().__init_subclass__(**kwargs)
505        cls._type_ = serializable_field(
506            init=True, repr=False, default=repr(cls), assert_type=False
507        )
508        cls.__annotations__["_type_"] = Literal[repr(cls)]  # type: ignore
509
510    def __hash__(self):
511        "Stable hash to identify unique `MazeTokenizerModular` instances. uses name"
512        return int.from_bytes(
513            hashlib.blake2b(self.name.encode("utf-8")).digest(),
514            byteorder="big",
515        )
516
517    @classmethod
518    def _level_one_subclass(cls) -> type["_TokenizerElement"]:
519        """Returns the immediate subclass of `_TokenizerElement` of which `cls` is an instance."""
520        return (
521            set(cls.__mro__).intersection(set(_TokenizerElement.__subclasses__())).pop()
522        )
523
524    def tokenizer_elements(self, deep: bool = True) -> list["_TokenizerElement"]:
525        """
526        Returns a list of all `_TokenizerElement` instances contained in the subtree.
527        Currently only detects `_TokenizerElement` instances which are either direct attributes of another instance or
528        which sit inside a `tuple` without further nesting.
529
530        # Parameters
531        - `deep: bool`: Whether to return elements nested arbitrarily deeply or just a single layer.
532        """
533        if not any(type(el) == tuple for el in self.__dict__.values()):
534            return list(
535                flatten(
536                    [
537                        [el] + el.tokenizer_elements()
538                        for el in self.__dict__.values()
539                        if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
540                    ]
541                )
542                if deep
543                else filter(
544                    lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement), self.__dict__.values()
545                )
546            )
547        else:
548            non_tuple_elems: list[_TokenizerElement] = list(
549                flatten(
550                    [
551                        [el] + el.tokenizer_elements()
552                        for el in self.__dict__.values()
553                        if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
554                    ]
555                    if deep
556                    else filter(
557                        lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement),
558                        self.__dict__.values(),
559                    )
560                )
561            )
562            tuple_elems: list[_TokenizerElement] = list(
563                flatten(
564                    [
565                        (
566                            [
567                                [tup_el] + tup_el.tokenizer_elements()
568                                for tup_el in el
569                                if isinstance(tup_el, _TokenizerElement)
570                            ]
571                            if deep
572                            else filter(lambda x: isinstance(x, _TokenizerElement), el)
573                        )
574                        for el in self.__dict__.values()
575                        if isinstance(el, tuple)
576                    ]
577                )
578            )
579            non_tuple_elems.extend(tuple_elems)
580            return non_tuple_elems
581
582    def tokenizer_element_tree(self, depth: int = 0, abstract: bool = False) -> str:
583        """
584        Returns a string representation of the tree of tokenizer elements contained in `self`.
585
586        # Parameters
587        - `depth: int`: Current depth in the tree. Used internally for recursion, no need to specify.
588        - `abstract: bool`: Whether to print the name of the abstract base class or the concrete class for each `_TokenizerElement` instance.
589        """
590        name: str = "\t" * depth + (
591            type(self).__name__
592            if not abstract
593            else type(self)._level_one_subclass().__name__
594        )
595        return (
596            name
597            + "\n"
598            + "".join(
599                el.tokenizer_element_tree(depth + 1, abstract)
600                for el in self.tokenizer_elements(deep=False)
601            )
602        )
603
604    def tokenizer_element_dict(self) -> dict:
605        """
606        Returns a dictionary representation of the tree of tokenizer elements contained in `self`.
607        """
608        return {
609            type(self).__name__: {
610                key: (
611                    val.tokenizer_element_dict()
612                    if isinstance(val, _TokenizerElement)
613                    else (
614                        val
615                        if not isinstance(val, tuple)
616                        else [
617                            (
618                                el.tokenizer_element_dict()
619                                if isinstance(el, _TokenizerElement)
620                                else el
621                            )
622                            for el in val
623                        ]
624                    )
625                )
626                for key, val in self.__dict__.items()
627                if key != "_type_"
628            }
629        }
630
631    @classmethod
632    @abc.abstractmethod
633    def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
634        """Returns the binding used in `MazeTokenizerModular` for that type of `_TokenizerElement`."""
635        raise NotImplementedError
636
637    def to_tokens(self, *args, **kwargs) -> list[str]:
638        """Converts a maze element into a list of tokens.
639        Not all `_TokenizerElement` subclasses produce tokens, so this is not an abstract method.
640        Those subclasses which do produce tokens should override this method.
641        """
642        raise NotImplementedError
643
644    @abc.abstractmethod
645    def is_valid(self) -> bool:
646        """Returns if `self` contains data members capable of producing an overall valid `MazeTokenizerModular`.
647        Some `_TokenizerElement` instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints.
648        `is_valid` allows for more precise detection of invalid `_TokenizerElement`s beyond type hinting alone.
649        If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply `return True` for that subclass.
650
651        # Types of Invalidity
652        In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below.
653        Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:
654        - Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study.
655        E.g., `_TokenizerElement`s which are strictly worse than some alternative.
656        - Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
657        - Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
658        - Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.
659
660        # Development
661        `is_invalid` is implemented to always return `True` in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid.
662        When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.
663
664        ## Nesting
665        In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call `is_valid` on nested `_TokenizerElement`s contained in the class.
666        In other words, failures of `is_valid` need not bubble up to the top of the nested `_TokenizerElement` tree.
667        `MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid` calls `is_valid` on each of its `_TokenizerElement`s individually, so failure at any level will be detected.
668
669        ## Types of Invalidity
670        If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments.
671        This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid `_TokenizerElement` instances.
672        """
673        raise NotImplementedError

Superclass for tokenizer elements. Subclasses contain modular functionality for maze tokenization.

Development

Due to the functionality of ALL_TOKENIZERS, _TokenizerElement subclasses may only contain fields of type utils.FiniteValued. Implementing a subclass with an int or float-typed field, for example, is not supported. In the event that adding such fields is deemed necessary, ALL_TOKENIZERS must be updated.

645    def is_valid(self) -> bool:
646        """Returns if `self` contains data members capable of producing an overall valid `MazeTokenizerModular`.
647        Some `_TokenizerElement` instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints.
648        `is_valid` allows for more precise detection of invalid `_TokenizerElement`s beyond type hinting alone.
649        If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply `return True` for that subclass.
650
651        # Types of Invalidity
652        In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below.
653        Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:
654        - Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study.
655        E.g., `_TokenizerElement`s which are strictly worse than some alternative.
656        - Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
657        - Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
658        - Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.
659
660        # Development
661        `is_invalid` is implemented to always return `True` in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid.
662        When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.
663
664        ## Nesting
665        In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call `is_valid` on nested `_TokenizerElement`s contained in the class.
666        In other words, failures of `is_valid` need not bubble up to the top of the nested `_TokenizerElement` tree.
667        `MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid` calls `is_valid` on each of its `_TokenizerElement`s individually, so failure at any level will be detected.
668
669        ## Types of Invalidity
670        If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments.
671        This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid `_TokenizerElement` instances.
672        """
673        raise NotImplementedError

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

1961    @staticmethod
1962    def _type_check(obj: any) -> None:
1963        """Helper method for `has_element`"""
1964        if not (
1965            isinstance(obj, _TokenizerElement)
1966            or (isinstance(obj, type) and issubclass(obj, _TokenizerElement))
1967        ):
1968            raise TypeError(f"{obj} is not a `_TokenizerElement` instance or subclass.")
1969
1970    def _has_element_singular(self, el: type[_TokenizerElement] | _TokenizerElement):
1971        """Helper method for `has_element`"""
1972        self._type_check(el)
1973        if isinstance(el, type):
1974            return any([isinstance(e, el) for e in self.tokenizer_elements])
1975        else:
1976            return el in self.tokenizer_elements
1977
1978    def has_element(
1979        self,
1980        *elements: Sequence[type[_TokenizerElement] | _TokenizerElement],
1981    ) -> bool:
1982        """Returns True if the `MazeTokenizerModular` instance contains ALL of the items specified in `elements`.
1983
1984        Querying with a partial subset of `_TokenizerElement` fields is not currently supported.
1985        To do such a query, assemble multiple calls to `has_elements`.
1986
1987        # Parameters
1988        - `elements`: Singleton or iterable of `_TokenizerElement` instances or classes.
1989        If an instance is provided, then comparison is done via instance equality.
1990        If a class is provided, then comparison isdone via `isinstance`. I.e., any instance of that class is accepted.
1991        """
1992        if len(elements) == 1 and isinstance(elements[0], Iterable):
1993            elements = elements[0]
1994        return all([self._has_element_singular(e) for e in elements])
1995
1996    def is_valid(self):
1997        """
1998        Returns `True` if `self` is a valid tokenizer.
1999        Evaluates the validity of all of `self.tokenizer_elements` according to each one's method.
2000        """
2001        return all([el.is_valid() for el in self.tokenizer_elements])
2002
2003    def is_legacy_equivalent(self) -> bool:
2004        """Returns if `self` has identical stringification behavior as any legacy `MazeTokenizer`."""
2005        return any(
2006            [
2007                self == MazeTokenizerModular.from_legacy(tok_mode)
2008                for tok_mode in TokenizationMode
2009            ]
2010        )
2011
2012    def is_tested_tokenizer(self) -> bool:
2013        """
2014        Returns if the tokenizer is returned by `all_tokenizers._get_all_tokenizers`, the set of tested and reliable tokenizers.
2015        Since evaluating `all_tokenizers._get_all_tokenizers` is expensive,
2016        instead checks for membership of `self`'s hash in `get_all_tokenizer_hashes()`.
2017        """
2018        all_tokenizer_hashes: Int64[np.ndarray, "n_tokenizers"] = (
2019            get_all_tokenizer_hashes()
2020        )
2021        hash_index: int = np.searchsorted(all_tokenizer_hashes, hash(self))
2022        return (
2023            hash_index < len(all_tokenizer_hashes)
2024            and all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] == hash(self)
2025            and self.is_valid()
2026        )

2028    def is_AOTP(self) -> bool:
2029        return self.has_element(PromptSequencers.AOTP)
2030
2031    def is_UT(self) -> bool:
2032        return self.has_element(CoordTokenizers.UT)

2121    @staticmethod
2122    def encode(text: str | list[str]) -> list[int]:
2123        """encode a string or list of strings into a list of tokens"""
2124        try:
2125            if isinstance(text, str):
2126                text = text.split()
2127            return [VOCAB_TOKEN_TO_INDEX[token] for token in text]
2128        except KeyError as e:
2129            raise TokenError(
2130                f"Token {e} not found",
2131                f"in `VOCAB`.",
2132            ) from e
2133
2134    @staticmethod
2135    def decode(
2136        token_ids: Sequence[int], joined_tokens: bool = False
2137    ) -> list[str] | str:
2138        """decode a list of tokens into a string or list of strings"""
2139        try:
2140            output: list[str] = [VOCAB_LIST[token_id] for token_id in token_ids]
2141        except IndexError as e:
2142            raise TokenError(f"Token index '{e}' not found in `VOCAB`.") from e
2143        if joined_tokens:
2144            return " ".join(output)
2145        else:
2146            return output

1990        If a class is provided, then comparison isdone via `isinstance`. I.e., any instance of that class is accepted.
1991        """
1992        if len(elements) == 1 and isinstance(elements[0], Iterable):
1993            elements = elements[0]
1994        return all([self._has_element_singular(e) for e in elements])

Returns True if the MazeTokenizerModular instance contains ALL of the items specified in elements.

Querying with a partial subset of _TokenizerElement fields is not currently supported. To do such a query, assemble multiple calls to has_elements.

Parameters

  • elements: Singleton or iterable of _TokenizerElement instances or classes. If an instance is provided, then comparison is done via instance equality. If a class is provided, then comparison isdone via isinstance. I.e., any instance of that class is accepted.

def is_tested_tokenizer(self) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
2012    def is_tested_tokenizer(self) -> bool:
2013        """
2014        Returns if the tokenizer is returned by `all_tokenizers._get_all_tokenizers`, the set of tested and reliable tokenizers.
2015        Since evaluating `all_tokenizers._get_all_tokenizers` is expensive,
2016        instead checks for membership of `self`'s hash in `get_all_tokenizer_hashes()`.
2017        """
2018        all_tokenizer_hashes: Int64[np.ndarray, "n_tokenizers"] = (
2019            get_all_tokenizer_hashes()
2020        )
2021        hash_index: int = np.searchsorted(all_tokenizer_hashes, hash(self))
2022        return (
2023            hash_index < len(all_tokenizer_hashes)
2024            and all_tokenizer_hashes[hash_index] == hash(self)
2025            and self.is_valid()
2026        )

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

1726        def _get_prompt_regions(
1727            self,
1728            maze: LatticeMaze,
1729            *args,
1730            **kwargs,
1731        ) -> list[list[str]]:
1732            """Gets the prompt regions of a maze in a fixed sequence.
1733
1734            This method is NOT responsible for including/excluding any prompt regions.
1735            Always return according to the API described under Returns.
1736            This implementation is expected to be suitable for most `PromptSequencer` subclasses.
1737            Subclasses may override this method if needed for special behavior.
1738
1739            # Returns
1740            - [0]: list[str] Adjacency list tokens
1741            - [1]: list[str] Origin tokens
1742            - [2]: list[str] Target tokens
1743            - [3]: list[str] Path tokens
1744
1745            # `None`-valued Args
1746            If one or more of `origin`, `target`, or `path` are `None`, that indicates that an unsolved or untargeted maze is being tokenized.
1747            To ensure unpackability in `_sequence_tokens`, these `None` values are substituted for empty iterables.
1748            """
1749            origin: Coord | None = getattr(maze, "start_pos", None)
1750            target: list[Coord] | None = [
1751                getattr(maze, "end_pos", None)
1752            ]  # TargetTokenizer requires target: Sequence[Coord]
1753
1754            return [
1755                (
1756                    self.adj_list_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1757                        maze, coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer
1758                    )
1759                    if hasattr(self, "adj_list_tokenizer")
1760                    else []
1761                ),
1762                self.coord_tokenizer.to_tokens(origin) if origin is not None else [],
1763                (
1764                    self.target_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1765                        target, coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer
1766                    )
1767                    if target[0] is not None and hasattr(self, "target_tokenizer")
1768                    else []
1769                ),
1770                (
1771                    self.path_tokenizer.to_tokens(
1772                        maze, coord_tokenizer=self.coord_tokenizer
1773                    )
1774                    if hasattr(maze, "solution") and hasattr(self, "path_tokenizer")
1775                    else []
1776                ),
1777            ]

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"

757                    elif field.loading_fn:

759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)

761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

class AdjListTokenizers(maze_dataset.tokenization.maze_tokenizer.__TokenizerElementNamespace):
View on GitHub 
1017class AdjListTokenizers(__TokenizerElementNamespace):
1018    key = "adj_list_tokenizer"
1019
1020    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1021    @mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: self_.pre is False)
1022    class _AdjListTokenizer(_TokenizerElement, abc.ABC):
1023        """
1024        Specifies how the adjacency list is tokenized.
1025        Tokenization behavior is decomposed into specification of edge subsets, groupings, and permutations.
1026        See documentation of `EdgeSubset` and `EdgeGrouping` classes for more details.
1027
1028        # Parameters
1029        - `pre`: Whether all edge groupings include a preceding delimiter token
1030        - `post`: Whether all edge groupings include a following delimiter token
1031        - `shuffle_d0`: Specifies how to sequence the edge groupings.
1032        If true, groupings are shuffled randomly. If false, groupings are sorted by the leading coord of each group.
1033        - `edge_grouping`: Specifies if/how multiple coord-coord connections are grouped together in a token subsequence called an edge grouping.
1034        - `edge_subset`: Specifies the subset of lattice edges to be tokenized.
1035        - `edge_permuter`: Specifies, in each edge tokenization, which coord either:
1036          1. Appears first in the tokenization, for `AdjListCoord`.
1037          2. Is tokenized directly as a coord, for `AdjListCardinal`.
1038          - `shuffle`: For each edge, the leading coord is selected randomly.
1039          - `all`: Each edge appears twice in the tokenization, appearing with both leading coords.
1040          - `evens`, `odds`: The leading coord is the one belonging to that coord subset. See `EdgeSubsets.ChessboardSublattice` for details.
1041        """
1042
1043        pre: bool = serializable_field(default=False, assert_type=False)
1044        post: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
1045        shuffle_d0: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
1046        edge_grouping: EdgeGroupings._EdgeGrouping = serializable_field(
1047            default=EdgeGroupings.Ungrouped(),
1048            loading_fn=lambda x: _load_tokenizer_element(x, EdgeGroupings),
1049        )
1050        edge_subset: EdgeSubsets._EdgeSubset = serializable_field(
1051            default=EdgeSubsets.ConnectionEdges(),
1052            loading_fn=lambda x: _load_tokenizer_element(x, EdgeSubsets),
1053        )
1054        edge_permuter: EdgePermuters._EdgePermuter = serializable_field(
1055            default=EdgePermuters.RandomCoords(),
1056            loading_fn=lambda x: _load_tokenizer_element(x, EdgePermuters),
1057        )
1058
1059        @classmethod
1060        def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
1061            return AdjListTokenizers.key
1062
1063        def is_valid(self) -> bool:
1064            # No invalid instances possible within data member type hint bounds
1065            return True
1066
1067        @abc.abstractmethod
1068        def _tokenization_callables(
1069            self,
1070            edges: ConnectionArray,
1071            is_conn: Bool[np.ndarray, "edges"],
1072            coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1073            *args,
1074            **kwargs,
1075        ):
1076            """
1077            Returns a sequence of callables which take an index in `edges` and return parts of that edge tokenization.
1078
1079            # Returns
1080            - `[0]`: leading coord tokens
1081            - `[1]`: connector tokens
1082            - `[2]`: trailing coord tokens
1083            """
1084            pass
1085
1086        def _tokenize_edge_grouping(
1087            self,
1088            edges: ConnectionArray,
1089            maze: LatticeMaze,
1090            coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1091            group_params: EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams,
1092        ) -> Sequence[str]:
1093            """
1094            Tokenizes a single edge grouping.
1095            """
1096            cxn_ord: int = group_params["connection_token_ordinal"]
1097            is_conn: Bool[np.ndarray, "edges"] = is_connection(
1098                edges, maze.connection_list
1099            )
1100            tokenize_callables = self._tokenization_callables(
1101                edges, is_conn, coord_tokenizer
1102            )
1103
1104            if group_params["grouped"]:
1105                # If grouped
1106                callable_permutation: list[int] = [1, 2] if cxn_ord == 0 else [2, 1]
1107                repeated_callables = [
1108                    tokenize_callables[i] for i in callable_permutation
1109                ]
1110                return flatten(
1111                    [
1112                        tokenize_callables[0](0),
1113                        [
1114                            [
1115                                *[
1116                                    tok_callable(i)
1117                                    for tok_callable in repeated_callables
1118                                ],
1119                                *(
1120                                    (VOCAB.ADJLIST_INTRA,)
1121                                    if group_params["intra"]
1122                                    else ()
1123                                ),
1124                            ]
1125                            for i in range(edges.shape[0])
1126                        ],
1127                    ]
1128                )
1129            else:
1130                # If ungrouped
1131                callable_permutation = [0, 2]
1132                callable_permutation.insert(cxn_ord, 1)
1133                tokenize_callables = [
1134                    tokenize_callables[i] for i in callable_permutation
1135                ]
1136
1137                return flatten(
1138                    [
1139                        [
1140                            [
1141                                *[
1142                                    tok_callable(i)
1143                                    for tok_callable in tokenize_callables
1144                                ],
1145                                *empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1146                                    (VOCAB.ADJLIST_INTRA,), group_params, "intra"
1147                                ),
1148                            ]
1149                            for i in range(edges.shape[0])
1150                        ]
1151                    ]
1152                )
1153
1154        def to_tokens(
1155            self, maze: LatticeMaze, coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer
1156        ) -> list[str]:
1157            # Get the set of edges to be tokenized
1158            edges: ConnectionArray = self.edge_subset._get_edges(maze)
1159            # Systematically permute the leading coord of each edge
1160            edges: ConnectionArray = self.edge_permuter._permute(edges)
1161            group_params: EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams = (
1162                self.edge_grouping._token_params()
1163            )
1164            # then, we need to group the edges
1165            groups: Sequence[ConnectionArray] = self.edge_grouping._group_edges(edges)
1166            # shuffle the groups if specified
1167            if self.shuffle_d0:
1168                if isinstance(groups, np.ndarray):
1169                    numpy_rng.shuffle(groups, axis=0)
1170                elif isinstance(groups, list):
1171                    random.shuffle(groups)
1172                else:
1173                    raise TypeError(
1174                        f"`groups` is an unexpected type {type(groups)}. Only types `list` and `np.ndarray` are currently supported."
1175                    )
1176            # Tokenize each group with optional delimiters
1177            tokens: list[str] = list(
1178                flatten(
1179                    [
1180                        [
1181                            *empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1182                                (VOCAB.ADJLIST_PRE,), self, "pre"
1183                            ),
1184                            *self._tokenize_edge_grouping(
1185                                group, maze, coord_tokenizer, group_params
1186                            ),
1187                            *empty_sequence_if_attr_false(
1188                                (VOCAB.ADJACENCY_ENDLINE,), self, "post"
1189                            ),
1190                        ]
1191                        for group in groups
1192                    ]
1193                )
1194            )
1195            return tokens

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

class EdgeGroupings(maze_dataset.tokenization.maze_tokenizer.__TokenizerElementNamespace):
View on GitHub 
775class EdgeGroupings(__TokenizerElementNamespace):
776    """Namespace for `EdgeGrouping` subclass hierarchy used by `AdjListTokenizer`."""
777
778    key = "edge_grouping"
779
780    class _GroupingTokenParams(TypedDict):
781        """A uniform private hyperparameter interface used by `AdjListTokenizer`."""
782
783        connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1, 2]
784        intra: bool
785        grouped: bool
786
787    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
788    class _EdgeGrouping(_TokenizerElement, abc.ABC):
789        """Specifies if/how multiple coord-coord connections are grouped together in a token subsequence called a edge grouping."""
790
791        @classmethod
792        def attribute_key(cls) -> str:
793            return EdgeGroupings.key
794
795        def is_valid(self) -> bool:
796            return True
797
798        @abc.abstractmethod
799        def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:
800            """Divides a ConnectionArray into groups of edges.
801            Shuffles/sequences within each group if applicable.
802            """
803            pass
804
805        @abc.abstractmethod
806        def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
807            """Returns the tok.nization hyperparameters necessary for an `AdjListTokenizer` to tokenize.
808
809            These hyperparameters are not used by `_EdgeGrouping` internally.
810            They are located in `_EdgeGrouping` rather than in `AdjListTokenizer`
811            since the hyperparameter space is a function of the `_EdgeGrouping` subclass.
812            This function resolves the `_EdgeGrouping` hyperparameter space which is non-uniform across subclasses
813            into a uniform private interface used by `AdjListTokenizer`.
814            """
815            pass
816
817    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
818    class Ungrouped(_EdgeGrouping):
819        """No grouping occurs, each edge is tokenized individually.
820
821        # Parameters
822        - `connection_token_ordinal`: At which index in the edge tokenization the connector (or wall) token appears.
823        Edge tokenizations contain 3 parts: a leading coord, a connector (or wall) token, and either a second coord or cardinal direction tokenization.
824        """
825
826        connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1, 2] = serializable_field(
827            default=1, assert_type=False
828        )
829
830        def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
831            return EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams(
832                connection_token_ordinal=self.connection_token_ordinal,
833                intra=False,
834                grouped=False,
835            )
836
837        def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionList) -> Sequence[ConnectionList]:
838            return np.expand_dims(edges, 1)
839
840    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
841    @mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: False)
842    class ByLeadingCoord(_EdgeGrouping):
843        """All edges with the same leading coord are grouped together.
844
845        # Parameters
846        - `intra`: Whether all edge groupings include a delimiter token between individual edge representations.
847        Note that each edge representation will already always include a connector token (`VOCAB.CONNECTOR`, or possibly `)
848        - `shuffle_group`: Whether the sequence of edges within the group should be shuffled or appear in a fixed order.
849        If false, the fixed order is lexicographical by (row, col).
850        In effect, lexicographical sorting sorts edges by their cardinal direction in the sequence NORTH, WEST, EAST, SOUTH, where the directions indicate the position of the trailing coord relative to the leading coord.
851        - `connection_token_ordinal`: At which index in token sequence representing a single edge the connector (or wall) token appears.
852        Edge tokenizations contain 2 parts: a connector (or wall) token and a coord or cardinal tokenization.
853        """
854
855        intra: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
856        shuffle_group: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
857        connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1] = serializable_field(
858            default=0, assert_type=False
859        )
860
861        def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
862            return EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams(
863                connection_token_ordinal=self.connection_token_ordinal,
864                intra=self.intra,
865                grouped=True,
866            )
867
868        def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:
869            # Adapted from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38013778/is-there-any-numpy-group-by-function
870            index_array: Int[np.ndarray, "sort_indices=edges"] = np.lexsort(
871                (edges[:, 1, 1], edges[:, 1, 0], edges[:, 0, 1], edges[:, 0, 0])
872            )
873            sorted_edges: ConnectionArray = edges[index_array, ...]
874            groups: list[ConnectionArray] = np.split(
875                sorted_edges,
876                np.unique(sorted_edges[:, 0, :], return_index=True, axis=0)[1][1:],
877            )
878            if self.shuffle_group:
879                [numpy_rng.shuffle(g, axis=0) for g in groups]
880            return groups

705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )

716            return result

def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

class EdgeGroupings.ByLeadingCoord(maze_dataset.tokenization.maze_tokenizer.EdgeGroupings._EdgeGrouping):
