840    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
841    @mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: False)
842    class ByLeadingCoord(_EdgeGrouping):
843        """All edges with the same leading coord are grouped together.
844
845        # Parameters
846        - `intra`: Whether all edge groupings include a delimiter token between individual edge representations.
847        Note that each edge representation will already always include a connector token (`VOCAB.CONNECTOR`, or possibly `)
848        - `shuffle_group`: Whether the sequence of edges within the group should be shuffled or appear in a fixed order.
849        If false, the fixed order is lexicographical by (row, col).
850        In effect, lexicographical sorting sorts edges by their cardinal direction in the sequence NORTH, WEST, EAST, SOUTH, where the directions indicate the position of the trailing coord relative to the leading coord.
851        - `connection_token_ordinal`: At which index in token sequence representing a single edge the connector (or wall) token appears.
852        Edge tokenizations contain 2 parts: a connector (or wall) token and a coord or cardinal tokenization.
853        """
854
855        intra: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
856        shuffle_group: bool = serializable_field(default=True)
857        connection_token_ordinal: Literal[0, 1] = serializable_field(
858            default=0, assert_type=False
859        )
860
861        def _token_params(self) -> "EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams":
862            return EdgeGroupings._GroupingTokenParams(
863                connection_token_ordinal=self.connection_token_ordinal,
864                intra=self.intra,
865                grouped=True,
866            )
867
868        def _group_edges(self, edges: ConnectionArray) -> Sequence[ConnectionArray]:
869            # Adapted from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38013778/is-there-any-numpy-group-by-function
870            index_array: Int[np.ndarray, "sort_indices=edges"] = np.lexsort(
871                (edges[:, 1, 1], edges[:, 1, 0], edges[:, 0, 1], edges[:, 0, 0])
872            )
873            sorted_edges: ConnectionArray = edges[index_array, ...]
874            groups: list[ConnectionArray] = np.split(
875                sorted_edges,
876                np.unique(sorted_edges[:, 0, :], return_index=True, axis=0)[1][1:],
877            )
878            if self.shuffle_group:
879                [numpy_rng.shuffle(g, axis=0) for g in groups]
880            return groups

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

903            """
904            Executes a permutation.
905            Warning: Caller should be aware that `lattice_edges` may be modified in-place depending on the subclass's implementation.
906
907            # Parameters
908            - `lattice_edges`: Array of lattice edges.

924                np.lexsort(

926                        lattice_edges[:, 1, 1],

930                    )

940        def _permute(lattice_edges: ConnectionArray) -> ConnectionArray:
941            numpy_rng.permuted(lattice_edges, axis=1, out=lattice_edges)

946        """Includes both possible permutations of every edge in the output.
947        Since input ConnectionList has only 1 instance of each edge,
948        a call to `BothCoords._permute` will modify `lattice_edges` in-place, doubling `shape[0]`.
949        """

952        def _permute(lattice_edges: ConnectionArray) -> ConnectionArray:
953            return np.append(lattice_edges, np.flip(lattice_edges, axis=1), axis=0)

731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

944    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
945    class BothCoords(_EdgePermuter):

947        Since input ConnectionList has only 1 instance of each edge,

 996        Only edges which contain a connection are tokenized.
 997        Alternatively, only edges which contain a wall are tokenized.
 998
 999        # Parameters
1000        - `walls`: Whether wall edges or connection edges are tokenized.
1001        If true, `VOCAB.ADJLIST_WALL` is used in place of `VOCAB.CONNECTOR`.
1002        """
1003

1005
1006        def _get_edges(self, maze: LatticeMaze) -> ConnectionArray:

1009                conn_list = np.logical_not(conn_list)
1010                conn_list[0, -1, :] = False
1011                conn_list[1, :, -1] = False

731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

def is_valid(self) -> bool:
View on GitHub 
1305        def is_valid(self) -> bool:
1306            # No invalid instances possible within data member type hint bounds
1307            return True

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

1331            """Returns steps as tuples of starting and ending positions for each step."""
1332            indices: list[int] = self._step_single_indices(maze)
1333            return [(start, end) for start, end in zip(indices[:-1], indices[1:])]
1334
1335        def is_valid(self) -> bool:
1336            # No invalid instances possible within data member type hint bounds
1337            return True
1338
1339    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1340    class Singles(_StepSize):
1341        """
1342        Every coord in `maze.solution` is represented.
1343        Legacy tokenizers all use this behavior.
1344        """
1345
1346        def _step_single_indices(self, maze: SolvedMaze) -> list[int]:
1347            """Returns the indices of `maze.solution` corresponding to the steps to be tokenized."""
1348            return list(range(maze.solution.shape[0]))
1349
1350    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1351    @mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: False)
1352    class Straightaways(_StepSize):
1353        """
1354        Only coords where the path turns are represented in the path.
1355        I.e., the path is represented as a sequence of straightaways,
1356        specified by the coords at the turns.
1357        """
1358
1359        def _step_single_indices(self, maze: SolvedMaze) -> list[int]:
1360            """Returns the indices of `maze.solution` corresponding to the steps to be tokenized."""
1361            last_turn_coord: Coord = maze.solution[0, ...]
1362            indices: list[int] = [0]
1363            for i, coord in enumerate(maze.solution):
1364                if coord[0] != last_turn_coord[0] and coord[1] != last_turn_coord[1]:
1365                    indices.append(i - 1)
1366                    last_turn_coord = maze.solution[i - 1, ...]
1367            indices.append(i)
1368            return indices
1369
1370    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1371    class Forks(_StepSize):
1372        """
1373        Only coords at forks, where the path has >=2 options for the next step are included.
1374        Excludes the option of backtracking.
1375        The starting and ending coords are always included.
1376        """
1377
1378        def _step_single_indices(self, maze: SolvedMaze) -> list[int]:
1379            """Returns the indices of `maze.solution` corresponding to the steps to be tokenized."""
1380            return maze.get_solution_forking_points(always_include_endpoints=True)[0]
1381
1382    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1383    @mark_as_unsupported(lambda self_: False)
1384    class ForksAndStraightaways(_StepSize):
1385        """
1386        Includes the union of the coords included by `Forks` and `Straightaways`.
1387        See documentation for those classes for details.
1388        """
1389
1390        def _step_single_indices(self, maze: SolvedMaze) -> list[int]:
1391            """Returns the indices of `maze.solution` corresponding to the steps to be tokenized."""
1392            return list(
1393                np.unique(
1394                    np.concatenate(
1395                        (
1396                            StepSizes.Straightaways()._step_single_indices(maze),
1397                            StepSizes.Forks()._step_single_indices(maze),
1398                        )
1399                    )
1400                )
1401            )

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

1469    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1470    class Relative(_StepTokenizer):
1471        """Tokenizes a solution step using relative first-person directions (right, left, forward, etc.).
1472        To simplify the indeterminacy, at the start of a solution the "agent" solving the maze is assumed to be facing NORTH.
1473        Similarly to `Cardinal`, the direction is that of the step from the starting position.
1474        """
1475
1476        def to_tokens(
1477            self, maze: SolvedMaze, start_index: int, end_index: int, **kwargs
1478        ) -> list[str]:
1479            if start_index == 0:
1480                start = maze.solution[0]
1481                previous = start + np.array([1, 0])
1482                return [
1483                    get_relative_direction(
1484                        np.concatenate(
1485                            (
1486                                np.expand_dims(previous, 0),
1487                                maze.solution[start_index : start_index + 2],
1488                            ),
1489                            axis=0,
1490                        )
1491                    )
1492                ]
1493            return [
1494                get_relative_direction(maze.solution[start_index - 1 : start_index + 2])
1495            ]

1504        """

751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
class StepTokenizers.Relative(maze_dataset.tokenization.maze_tokenizer.StepTokenizers._StepTokenizer):
View on GitHub 
1469    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1470    class Relative(_StepTokenizer):
1471        """Tokenizes a solution step using relative first-person directions (right, left, forward, etc.).
1472        To simplify the indeterminacy, at the start of a solution the "agent" solving the maze is assumed to be facing NORTH.
1473        Similarly to `Cardinal`, the direction is that of the step from the starting position.
1474        """
1475
1476        def to_tokens(
1477            self, maze: SolvedMaze, start_index: int, end_index: int, **kwargs
1478        ) -> list[str]:
1479            if start_index == 0:
1480                start = maze.solution[0]
1481                previous = start + np.array([1, 0])
1482                return [
1483                    get_relative_direction(
1484                        np.concatenate(
1485                            (
1486                                np.expand_dims(previous, 0),
1487                                maze.solution[start_index : start_index + 2],
1488                            ),
1489                            axis=0,
1490                        )
1491                    )
1492                ]
1493            return [
1494                get_relative_direction(maze.solution[start_index - 1 : start_index + 2])
1495            ]

735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

1530        """Superclass of tokenizers for maze solution paths."""
1531

1534            self, maze: SolvedMaze, coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer
1535        ) -> list[str]:
1536            """Returns tokens representing the solution path."""
1537            pass
1538

1542
1543    @serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1544    class StepSequence(_PathTokenizer, abc.ABC):
1545        """Any `PathTokenizer` where the tokenization may be assembled from token subsequences, each of which represents a step along the path.
1546        Allows for a sequence of leading and trailing tokens which don't fit the step pattern.
1547
1548        # Parameters
1549        - `step_size`: Selects the size of a single step in the sequence
1550        - `step_tokenizers`: Selects the combination and permutation of tokens
1551        - `pre`: Whether all steps include an integral preceding delimiter token
1552        - `intra`: Whether all steps include a delimiter token after each individual `_StepTokenizer` tokenization.
1553        - `post`: Whether all steps include an integral following delimiter token
1554        """
1555
1556        step_size: StepSizes._StepSize = serializable_field(
1557            default=StepSizes.Singles(),
1558            loading_fn=lambda x: _load_tokenizer_element(x, StepSizes),
1559        )
1560        step_tokenizers: StepTokenizers.StepTokenizerPermutation = serializable_field(
1561            default=(StepTokenizers.Coord(),),
1562            serialization_fn=lambda x: [y.serialize() for y in x],
1563            loading_fn=lambda x: tuple(x[StepTokenizers.key]),
1564        )
1565        pre: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1566        intra: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1567        post: bool = serializable_field(default=False)
1568
1569        def to_tokens(
1570            self, maze: SolvedMaze, coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer
1571        ) -> list[str]:
1572            return [
1573                *self._leading_tokens(maze, coord_tokenizer),
1574                *flatten(
1575                    [
1576                        self._single_step_tokens(maze, start, end, coord_tokenizer)
1577                        for start, end in self.step_size.step_start_end_indices(maze)
1578                    ]
1579                ),
1580                *self._trailing_tokens(maze, coord_tokenizer),
1581            ]
1582
1583        def _single_step_tokens(
1584            self,
1585            maze: SolvedMaze,
1586            i: int,
1587            j: int,
1588            coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer,
1589        ) -> list[str]:
1590            """Returns the token sequence representing a single step along the path."""
1591            step_rep_tokens: list[list[str]] = [
1592                step_tokenizer.to_tokens(maze, i, j, coord_tokenizer=coord_tokenizer)
1593                for step_tokenizer in self.step_tokenizers
1594            ]
1595            if self.intra:
1596                step_rep_tokens_and_intra: list[str] = [None] * (
1597                    len(step_rep_tokens) * 2
1598                )
1599                step_rep_tokens_and_intra[::2] = step_rep_tokens
1600                step_rep_tokens_and_intra[1::2] = [VOCAB.PATH_INTRA] * len(
1601                    step_rep_tokens
1602                )
1603                step_rep_tokens = list(flatten(step_rep_tokens_and_intra))
1604            all_tokens: list[str] = [
1605                *empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_PRE,), self, "pre"),
1606                *flatten(step_rep_tokens),
1607                *empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_POST,), self, "post"),
1608            ]
1609            return all_tokens
1610
1611        def _leading_tokens(
1612            self, maze: SolvedMaze, coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer
1613        ) -> list[str]:
1614            """Returns tokens preceding those from the sequence from `_single_step_tokens`.
1615            Since the for loop in `to_tokens` iterates `len(path)-1` times, a fencepost problem exists with `StepTokenizers.Coord`.
1616            <PATH_START> should NOT be included.
1617            """
1618            if StepTokenizers.Coord() in self.step_tokenizers:
1619                return [
1620                    *empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_PRE,), self, "pre"),
1621                    *coord_tokenizer.to_tokens(maze.solution[0, ...]),
1622                    *empty_sequence_if_attr_false((VOCAB.PATH_INTRA,), self, "intra"),
1623                ]
1624            return []
1625
1626        def _trailing_tokens(
1627            self, c: Coord, coord_tokenizer: CoordTokenizers._CoordTokenizer
1628        ) -> list[str]:
1629            """Returns tokens following those from the sequence from `_single_step_tokens`.
1630            <PATH_END> should NOT be included.
1631            """
1632            return []
1633
1634        def is_valid(self) -> bool:
1635            if len(set(self.step_tokenizers)) != len(self.step_tokenizers):
1636                # Uninteresting: repeated elements are not useful
1637                return False
1638
1639            if len(self.step_tokenizers) == 1 and isinstance(
1640                self.step_tokenizers[0], StepTokenizers.Distance
1641            ):
1642                # Untrainable: `Distance` alone cannot encode a path. >=1 `StepTokenizer` which indicates direction/location is required.
1643                return False
1644            else:
1645                return True

Returns if self contains data members capable of producing an overall valid MazeTokenizerModular. Some _TokenizerElement instances may be created which are not useful despite obeying data member type hints. is_valid allows for more precise detection of invalid _TokenizerElements beyond type hinting alone. If type hints are sufficient to constrain the possible instances of some subclass, then this method may simply return True for that subclass.

Types of Invalidity

In nontrivial implementations of this method, each conditional clause should contain a comment classifying the reason for invalidity and one of the types below. Invalidity types, in ascending order of invalidity:

  • Uninteresting: These tokenizers might be used to train functional models, but the schemes are not interesting to study. E.g., _TokenizerElements which are strictly worse than some alternative.
  • Duplicate: These tokenizers have identical tokenization behavior as some other valid tokenizers.
  • Untrainable: Training functional models using these tokenizers would be (nearly) impossible.
  • Erroneous: These tokenizers might raise exceptions during use.

Development

is_invalid is implemented to always return True in some abstract classes where all currently possible subclass instances are valid. When adding new subclasses or data members, the developer should check if any such blanket statement of validity still holds and update it as neccesary.

Nesting

In general, when implementing this method, there is no need to recursively call is_valid on nested _TokenizerElements contained in the class. In other words, failures of is_valid need not bubble up to the top of the nested _TokenizerElement tree. MazeTokenizerModular.is_valid calls is_valid on each of its _TokenizerElements individually, so failure at any level will be detected.

Types of Invalidity

If it's judged to be useful, the types of invalidity could be implemented with an Enum or similar rather than only living in comments. This could be used to create more or less stringent filters on the valid _TokenizerElement instances.

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator
